 a [default stylesheet](https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@observablehq/inspector@3/dist/inspector.css) ([see source](https://github.com/observablehq/inspector/blob/master/src/style.css)) if you want it. To make your embedded notebook beautiful, try a CSS framework. We favor [Tachyons](http://tachyons.io/) here at Observable, but there are lots of good choices, such as GitHub‚Äôs [Primer](https://primer.style/css).`","pinCode":false}}},{"type":"codeTool","data":{"codeData":{"value":"md`If you don‚Äôt want to render the entire notebook, define a custom function to control which cells are rendered and where they go. For example, to render just the cell named ‚Äúchart‚Äù into the DOM element with the same id, say:\n\n~~~js\nnew Runtime().module(notebook, name => {\n  if (name === \"chart\") {\n    return new Inspector(document.querySelector(\"#chart\"));\n  }\n});\n~~~`","pinCode":false}}},{"type":"codeTool","data":{"codeData":{"value":"md`It‚Äôs important to note that when you render a limited set of cells from your notebook, the cells that aren‚Äôt used ‚Äî or depended on by those that are ‚Äî won‚Äôt be run at all!`","pinCode":false}}},{"type":"codeTool","data":{"codeData":{"value":"md`Sometimes a cell that‚Äôs not referenced has important side effects, as in the [Sortable Bar Chart](https://observablehq.com/@d3/sortable-bar-chart), where an \\\\\\`update\\\\\\` cell passes data to the chart via a method that mutates the existing DOM element. If you want to run a cell with side effects in the background of your embedded notebook, you can return \\\\\\`true\\\\\\` instead of an inspector for those cells:\n\n~~~js\n(new Runtime).module(define, name => {\n  if (name === \"chart\") return Inspector.into(\".chart\")();\n  if (name === \"update\") return true;\n});\n~~~`","pinCode":false}}},{"type":"codeTool","data":{"codeData":{"value":"md`The code generated by the Embed tool uses this technique to run any cells that refer to one of the cells you‚Äôre embedding. If that‚Äôs o