(notebook, name => {\n  switch (name) {\n    case \"viewof selection\": return new Inspector(container);\n    case \"selection\": return {fulfilled(value) { setSelection(value); }};\n  }\n});\n~~~`","pinCode":false}}},{"type":"codeTool","data":{"codeData":{"value":"md`Sometimes you just want the current value of a cell. For that, you don‚Äôt need a proper *observer*; instead, use [*module*.value](https://github.com/observablehq/runtime/blob/master/README.md#module_value) to get a promise to the current value of the cell with the given name.\n\n~~~js\nconst module = new Runtime().module(notebook);\nconst value = await module.value(\"chart\");\ndocument.querySelector(\"#chart\").appendChild(value);\n~~~`","pinCode":false}}},{"type":"codeTool","data":{"codeData":{"value":"redefine = (md`## Overriding cell values\n\nIn addition to observing reactive values, your JavaScript program can assign reactive values, too, allowing bidirectional dataflow. For example, say you have a [bar chart](/@d3/bar-chart), and your application wants to update the displayed data dynamically. First, keep a reference to the main module for your notebook:\n\n~~~js\nconst main = new Runtime().module(notebook, name => {\n  if (name === \"chart\") {\n    return new Inspector(container);\n  }\n});\n~~~`)","pinCode":false}}},{"type":"codeTool","data":{"codeData":{"value":"md`Then whenever you want to change the chart‚Äôs data, call [*module*.redefine](https://github.com/observablehq/runtime/blob/master/README.md#module_redefine):\n\n~~~js\nmain.redefine(\"data\", newData);\n~~~`","pinCode":false}}},{"type":"codeTool","data":{"codeData":{"value":"md`Because Observable uses dataflow, the chart will update automatically in response to the new data, and the inspector will replace the contents of the chart‚Äôs *container*. You can pass *module*.redefine a constant value, a function that references other cell values‚Äîeven a [generator](/@observablehq/introduction-to-generators) function that repeatedly yi